      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Agent Commission Structures in Queensland: Tiered, Flat, and Percentage Explained
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The commission number you are quoted matters less than the structure behind it. Different structures push agents toward different behaviours during your campaign.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When Queensland was deregulated for real estate commission in 2014, agents were given freedom to negotiate their own fees with sellers. The result is a market where the headline percentage looks similar across most agencies, usually somewhere between 2.0 and 3.0 per cent of the sale price plus marketing, but the underlying structure of how that fee is calculated can vary considerably. The structure you agree to in your listing authority changes what your agent is financially motivated to do once your campaign is live, and that is worth understanding before you sign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Flat percentage commission</h2>
      <p>The simplest and most common structure is a flat percentage of the final sale price. The agent quotes a single percentage, for example 2.5 per cent, and that rate applies regardless of what the property eventually sells for. If your home sells for $1.4 million, the commission is $35,000 plus GST. If it sells for $1.2 million, the commission is $30,000 plus GST.</p>

      <p>The flat percentage is easy to understand and easy to compare between agencies. Its limitation is that it gives the agent a relatively flat marginal incentive across the price range. The difference in commission between selling at $1.2 million and selling at $1.4 million is $5,000, which sounds significant until you remember that the seller is gaining $200,000 from that price difference. A rational agent would push for the higher price either way, but the structure does not strongly tilt them toward holding out for an extra week to chase a stronger offer when a quick sale at a lower price still pays acceptably.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Tiered or incentivised commission</h2>
      <p>A tiered structure is designed to fix that flat-incentive problem. The agent quotes a base percentage that applies up to a target price, and a higher percentage on any portion of the sale price that exceeds the target. For example, the structure might be 2.0 per cent on the first $1.3 million and 10 per cent on every dollar above $1.3 million. If the property sells for $1.3 million, the commission is $26,000. If it sells for $1.4 million, the commission jumps to $36,000, because the agent earns an extra $10,000 on the $100,000 above target.</p>

      <p>This structure aligns the agent's incentive with the seller's interest in achieving the best possible price. The agent now has a strong financial reason to hold out for a stretch offer rather than recommend the seller accept a comfortable in-range one. The challenge is setting the target. Set it too low and the agent is incentivised on outcomes that would have happened anyway. Set it too high and the structure becomes a flat percentage in practice because the bonus tier never triggers.</p>

      <p>A reasonable approach is to anchor the target to the upper end of the agent's appraisal range. If the agent has appraised the property at $1.25 million to $1.35 million, setting the bonus tier to start at $1.35 million asks the agent to outperform their own honest assessment to earn the higher rate. That is a structure worth signing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Flat dollar or fixed-fee commission</h2>
      <p>A small number of agents quote a fixed dollar fee that does not vary with the sale price. The seller pays, for example, $30,000 regardless of whether the property sells for $1.1 million or $1.5 million. The fixed fee is most often associated with discount or low-cost agencies that compete on price rather than on result.</p>

      <p>The structural problem with a fixed fee is that it removes the agent's incentive to push for a higher price entirely. Once the property is under contract at any acceptable level, the agent is paid the same. The seller carries all the upside and all the downside of price negotiation alone. For an experienced seller who will personally drive the negotiation and campaign decisions, that may be acceptable. For a seller who is relying on the agent to fight for the best outcome, a fixed-fee structure works against you.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How marketing fits with each structure</h2>
      <p>Across all three commission structures, marketing costs are usually billed separately and are not included in the percentage or fee. This is true whether the agent quotes a vendor-paid marketing budget upfront or offers to fund marketing in exchange for a higher commission rate.</p>

      <p>Be wary of any agent who folds marketing into commission without breaking out the actual cost. The transparency matters because marketing is a sunk cost that you pay regardless of whether the property sells. Knowing what you are paying for portals, photography, signboards, video, and editorial gives you the information to question line items that are not pulling weight on your specific campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Which structure suits which seller?</h2>
      <p>For a straightforward sale where the agent's appraisal range feels accurate and you have confidence in the agent's competence, a flat percentage is fine. It is simple, predictable, and the dollar amounts are easy to verify against the contract.</p>

      <p>For a sale where you believe the property has genuine upside potential beyond the obvious comparable sales, or where you are working with an agent whose recent results suggest they consistently outperform the market, a tiered structure with a properly set bonus threshold is the better choice. You pay slightly less if the result is ordinary and significantly more if the result is exceptional. That is the right alignment.</p>

      <p>A fixed fee is rarely the right structure for a seller who values agent advocacy in the negotiation phase. The savings on the headline number are routinely consumed by softer negotiation outcomes, and the seller walks away with a similar or worse net position than they would have under a percentage structure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to ask before signing</h2>
      <p>Ask the agent to walk you through three scenarios: a sale at the bottom of their appraisal range, a sale in the middle, and a sale 5 per cent above the top of the range. The total commission and marketing for each scenario should be stated as a dollar figure inclusive of GST. Comparing those three numbers across two or three agents gives you a clearer view than comparing percentage rates in isolation.</p>

      <p>Ask whether the agent is open to a tiered structure if they have quoted you a flat percentage. The willingness, or unwillingness, to take some performance risk on their own fee tells you something about how confident they are in the appraisal they have given you.</p>

      <p>Ask what the listing authority says about commission if the property is withdrawn or if the agency falls out of the picture during the campaign. The standard authority documents protect the agent's commission if they introduced a buyer who later returns. Read those clauses carefully before signing.</p>

